<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN238">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>kavicen tāḻik kuvipuṟat tirunta</l>
<l>ceviceñ cēvalum pokuvalum veruvā</l>
<l>vāyvaṉ kākkaiyuṅ kūkaiyuṅ kūṭip</l>
<l>pēe yāyamoṭu peṭṭāṅku vaḻaṅkuṅ</l>
<l>kāṭumuṉ ṉiṉaṉē kaṭkā muṟunaṉ</l>
<l>ṟoṭikaḻi makaḷiriṟ ṟolkaviṉ vāṭip</l>
<l>pāṭunar kaṭumpum paiyeṉ ṟaṉavē</l>
<l>tōṭukoṇ muracuṅ kiḻintaṉa kaṇṇē</l>
<l>yāḷil varaipōl yāṉaiyu maruppiḻan taṉavē</l>
<l>ventiṟṟa kūṟṟam perumpē tuṟuppa</l>
<l>ventai yākuta lataṟpaṭa laṟiyē</l>
<l>ṉantō vaḷiyēṉ vantaṉeṉ maṉṟa</l>
<l>veṉṉa kuvarkoleṟ ṟuṉṉi yōrē</l>
<l>māri yiraviṉ maraṅkaviḻ poḻuti</l>
<l>ṉāraña ruṟṟa neñcamō ṭorāṅkuk</l>
<l>kaṇṇi lūmaṉ kaṭaṟpaṭ ṭāṅku</l>
<l>varaiyaḷan taṟiyāt tiraiyaru nīttat</l>
<l>tavala maṟucuḻi maṟukaliṟ</l>
<l>tavalē naṉṟumaṟ ṟakutiyu matuvē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>He who has a desire for toddy has approached the cremation ground, (5)</l>
<l>where the strong-mouthed crow and the owl meet, (3)</l>
<l>not being frightened by the cock red on the ear and the Pokuval(?) (2)</l>
<l>that perched on the back of the covered red urns, (1)</l>
<l>[and] where the Pēy roam at will, along with [their female] companions. (4)</l>
<l>The old beauty of [his] bangleless women fades (6)</l>
<l>[and] the relations of those who sing have become dull. (7)</l>
<l>The eyes of all the many drums have been torn (8)</l>
<l>and the manless mountain-like elephants have lost [their] tusks. (9)</l>
<l>In order to confuse Kūṟṟam of hot power (10)</l>
<l>I don’t know how that is to happen that he is my father [once more](?). (11)</l>
<l>Thus as one to be pitied I have come indeed. (12)</l>
<l>What will become of those who are near to me? (13)</l>
<l>At a time when trees are upturned in the night of showers, (14)</l>
<l>just as with a heart that had difficult grief, (15)</l>
<l>like an eyeless dumbman falling into the sea, (16)</l>
<l>like in a curving whirling of a whirl of affliction (17)</l>
<l>in a difficult flood of waves that do not know of being measured to the limit, (18)</l>
<l>death is something good certainly and it is proper. (19)</l>
</lg>
